<br>
<big><b>Study Tour Map: Western Cuba</b></big><br>
</div>
<img src="cuba_rel94f.jpg" alt="Large-scale Map" height="511"
 width="729"> <br>
<small><font face="Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif"> Source: Central
Intelligence
Agency</font></small><br>
<b><br>
</b>In March 2003, the off-beat comic strip <a
 href="http://www.zippythepinhead.com/"> Zippy the Pinhead</a> - which
often references unusual tourist landmarks - made mention of one of
Havana's most endearing attractions: the Coco taxis. Note the tourist's
KFC t-shirt. KFC is not in Cuba yet, but its parent company, Pepsico,
is
well represented (through off-shore subsidiaries, of course). Learn all
about
Zippy's 1994 adventures in Cuba from <a
 href="http://zippythepinhead.com/Merchant2/merchant.mv?Screen=PROD&amp;Product_Code=ZQ10&amp;Category_Code=cc&amp;Product_Count=9">
Zippy Quarterly #10</a>
.<br>
<br>
<div align="center"><a href="http://www.zippythepinhead.com/"><img
 src="../GRAPHICS/cubazippy.jpg" alt="Coco taxis rule!" border="0"
 height="244" width="849"> <br>
</a><small><small><font face="Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif">Copyright
2003 Bill
Griffith -- Used by Permission</font></small></small><br>
<a href="http://www.zippythepinhead.com/"><br>
